Planning a city trip around Europe

Exercise 1: Discovering Barcelona (4 Points)

We‚Äôre planning a weekend city trip around Europe and want to use geospatial data science tools to support our planning. First stop is Barcelona. We‚Äôll work with the {osmdata} and {tmap} packages.

  1. Use the appropriate function from {osmdata} to extract both the bounding box matrix and the polygon format for ‚ÄúBarcelona‚Äù. Briefly explain in 1‚Äì2 sentences why we might want to use one over the other in different mapping or data extraction scenarios.

Note: When using getbb(‚Ä¶, format_out = ‚Äúsf_polygon‚Äù), the result is a list containing both ‚Äúpolygon‚Äù and ‚Äúmultipolygon‚Äù formats. Select the ‚Äúmultipolygon‚Äù object for better accuracy in boundary mapping.

The matrix format is simpler and more efficient for quick bounding-box queries or base maps, while the polygon format provides more accurate city boundaries, which is useful for precise spatial operations or when visual accuracy matters in mapping.

# Installing and Loading librarys
#install.packages("osmdata")
#install.packages("tmap")

library(osmdata)
library(tmap)

# Searching for bounding box matrix and polygon formats
#?osmdata

# Bounding Box
bb_Barcelona <- getbb("Barcelona", format_out = "matrix") # matrix is default

# Polygon to Multipolygon
bb_poly_Barcelona <- getbb("Barcelona", format_out = "sf_polygon")
bb_poly_Barcelona <- bb_poly_Barcelona$multipolygon

Explanation

On the one hand the bounding-box matrix is extremely fast and lightweight, which makes it ideal for fast queries. On the other hand, multipolygon boundarys captures the ‚Äútrue‚Äù map, with all its irregular shapes, accurate area, etc., which makes it less usefull for fast queries.

  1. Create two different plots of the city outline using the polygon format: one interactive and one non-interactive. Customize the plots so that:
  • The borders are shown in ‚Äúdarkblue‚Äù
  • You add a title to each map using tm_layout
  • The interactive map allows zooming and panning

  1. Briefly describe the pros and cons of interactive maps and non-interactive maps based on the example you created in b) with one sentence each.

Interactive View

(+) Allows users to zoom and pan for more detailed boundary view.

(+) The interactive view also allows the users to see the map in different planes.

(-) Can be less usefull for printed documents or presentations.

(-) May require more resources.

Non-Interactive View

(+) Produces a clean and static view of the map, which can be used for printed documents or presentation.

(-) Does not allow users to see more areas of interest or to customize the view.

  1. Use the bounding box matrix to download all museums in Barcelona using the Overpass API via {osmdata}. Then display their locations on a static map using {tmap}.

Customize the map so that: - Museums are shown as red dots. - You use tm_basemap(‚ÄúOpenStreetMap‚Äù) for context. - You add a title indicating it‚Äôs a map of museums.

# Get all museums 
bb_Barcelona_museums <- bb_Barcelona %>%
  opq() %>%
  add_osm_feature(key = "tourism", value = "museum") %>% # museums are under the key tourism
  osmdata_sf()

bb_Barcelona_museums <- bb_Barcelona_museums$osm_points

# Static Map View
tmap_mode("plot")
tm_basemap("OpenStreetMap") + 
  tm_shape(bb_Barcelona_museums) + 
  # Adding red dots with black borders
  tm_symbols(col = "red", size = 0.3, border.col = "black", border.lwd = 0.5) +
  tm_layout(
    title = "Museums in Barcelona",
    frame = FALSE
  )

Exercise 2: Finding Accommodation in Berlin (5 Points)

Oops, we spent too much money in Barcelona. On our next stop in Berlin, we‚Äôd like to plan more budget-friendly and find a simple accommodation option such as a hostel. For this, we‚Äôll be using OpenStreetMaps.

  1. Search for the correct tag to identify affordable accommodation in OpenStreetMaps. Write down the tag below and add the URL to its OSMWiki page.

    Tag: tourism=hostel

    OSMWiki page: https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Tag:tourism%3Dhostel

  2. Write an {osmdata} query that downloads all hostels in Berlin using a bounding box. How many hostels are there in Berlin? Explain how you interpret points, polygons, and lines in the query results. If no lines are returned (as is often the case for buildings), explain why this is expected.

# Getting bounding box for Berlin
bb_berlin <- getbb("Berlin", format_out = "matrix")

# Query for all object tagged tourism=hostel
bb_berlin <- bb_berlin %>%
  opq() %>%
  add_osm_feature(key = "tourism", value = "hostel") %>%
  osmdata_sf()

# Getting hostels
bb_berlin_points   <- nrow(bb_berlin$osm_points)
bb_berlin_polygons <- nrow(bb_berlin$osm_polygons) + nrow(bb_berlin$osm_multipolygons)
bb_berlin_lines    <- nrow(bb_berlin$osm_lines)

cat("Hostel in Berlin:\n",
    "- Points:   ", bb_berlin_points,   "\n",
    "- Polygons: ", bb_berlin_polygons, "\n",
    "- Lines:    ", bb_berlin_lines,    "\n"
    )
Hostel in Berlin:
 - Points:    708 
 - Polygons:   
 - Lines:

Interpretation

  • Points are single OSM nodes tagged as a value, where only a location marker is needed.

  • Polygons represent mapped values/areas, where the item usually has a building footprint or property boundary.

  • Lines would capture linear features tagged as the value. Which is very uncommon for hostels, since they are places and not linear ways. Which explains why we expected 0 or NULL.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(dev = "ragg_png")

  1. Load the {matches.csv} file from the {data} folder. Visualize how the number of total goals scored per game has evolved over time. Create a nice and complete plot and interpret what you see in one or two sentences.
# Installing data
matches <- readr::read_csv(
  "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jfjelstul/englishfootball/master/data-csv/matches.csv"
)

# Compute total goals in each match and extract season‚Äôs start year
matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(
    total_goals  = home_team_score + away_team_score,
    season_start = as.integer(str_sub(season, 1, 4))
  )

# average goals per game by season
goals_by_season <- matches %>%
  group_by(season_start) %>%
  summarize(avg_goals = mean(total_goals, na.rm = TRUE))

# Plot static
game_static <- ggplot(goals_by_season, aes(x = season_start, y = avg_goals)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkgreen", size = 1) +
  geom_point(color = "darkgreen", size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1890, 2020, by = 10)) +
  labs(
    title = "Average Total Goals per Match Over Time",
    x     = "Season",
    y     = "Average Goals per Game"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

game_static

Interpretation

We can see, that the average goals per game started high, then it went down. During the interwar years it went higher, but went again lower and now it swings around 2,65 goals per game.

  1. Now create an animated version of your plot and include the GIF in your HTML
# Dynamic Plot
game_animated_plot <- game_static + transition_reveal(along = season_start)

# creating animation
game_anim <- animate(
  game_animated_plot,
  duration = 10,          # Duration in seconds
  fps      = 15,
  width    = 800,
  height   = 400,
  renderer = gifski_renderer(loop = TRUE)
)

anim_save("matches_animation.gif", animation = game_anim)
knitr::include_graphics("matches_animation.gif")

  1. Load the {standings.csv} dataset. We will now analyze how Liverpool FC has performed over the years. Create an animated plot that contains the number of points and the final placement of LFC for every year they have participated in professional football. The exact visualization is up to you.
# Loading the data
standings <- read_csv(
  "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jfjelstul/englishfootball/master/data-csv/standings.csv"
)

# Filtering for Liverpool FC
lfc <- standings %>%
  filter(team_name == "Liverpool")

lfc <- lfc %>%
  mutate(year = as.integer(substr(season, 1, 4)))

lfc_long <- lfc %>%
  select(year, points, position, season) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols      = c(points, position),
    names_to  = "metric",
    values_to = "value"
  )

# Plot
lfc_plot <- ggplot(lfc_long, aes(x = year, y = value, color = metric)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_wrap(~ metric, scales = "free_y", ncol = 1,
             labeller = as_labeller(c(points = "Points", position = "Final Position"))) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(lfc_long$year), max(lfc_long$year), by = 5)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(points = "firebrick", position = "steelblue")) +
  labs(
    title = "Liverpool FC Performance ‚Äî Season {frame_along}",
    x     = "Season (start year)",
    y     = NULL,
    color = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    strip.text   = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12),
    plot.title   = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
    axis.text.x  = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
  )
# Animation
lfc_plot_anim <- lfc_plot + transition_reveal(year) # Animate over the 'year' variable

  lfc_performance <- animate(
    lfc_plot_anim,
    fps      = 10,
    duration = 12,
    width    = 600,
    height   = 600,
    renderer = gifski_renderer(loop = TRUE)
  )

anim_save("lfc_performance.gif", animation = lfc_performance)
knitr::include_graphics("lfc_performance.gif")
